# HTMl forms 
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<meta charset="utf-8">
	<title>Register</title>
</head>
<body>
<form>
	First Name: <input type="text" required><br>
	Last Name: <input type="text"><br>
	Birth Day: <input type="date"><br> #you can do date
	Who do I love?:<br> # radio is a select button (need to specify name)
	<input type="radio" name = "who">Jack<br>
	<input type="radio" name = "who">Jack<br>
	<input type="radio" name = "who">Jack<br>
	Animals? : <br> # checkbox is well, a check box (specify a name)
	<input type="checkbox" name = "animal">Dog<br>
	<input type="checkbox" name = "animal">Cat<br>
	Email: <input type="email"><br> # you can do email! probably a lot of other validation
	<input type="submit" value="Register!">
	<input type="reset">
</form>
</body>
</html>

#HTML forms 2
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<meta charset="utf-8">
	<title>Register</title>
</head>
<body>
<form>
	First Name: <input type="text" name="firstname" required><br>
	Last Name: <input type="text" name="lastname"><br>
	Birth Day: <input type="date" name="birth"><br>
	Who do I love?:<br>
	<input type="radio" name = "who">Jack<br>
	<input type="radio" name = "who">Jack<br>
	<input type="radio" name = "who">Jack<br>
	Animals? : <br>
	<input type="checkbox" name = "animal">Dog<br>
	<input type="checkbox" name = "animal">Cat<br>
	Email: <input type="email" name="email"><br>
	Cars: <br>
	<select>
		<option value="volvo" name="volvo">Tesla</option>
		<option value="rivian" name="rivian">Rivian</option>
	</select><br>
	Password: <input type="password" min="5" name="password"><br>
	<input type="submit" value="Register!">
	<input type="reset">
</form>
</body>
</html>

Once you assign names everywhere, you can actually submit. this is called a query tag that is created
file:///Volumes/GoogleDrive/My%20Drive/Web%20Development%20%20%20UI%20%20%20UX/register.html?firstname=h&lastname=b&birth=9888-09-08&who=on&animal=on&email=haileytucker_10%40hotmail.com&password=halkjdklj 

? the question mark says that we will start giving you lots of data 
url encoding, it encodes the @ sign with %40 

